\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 2. R. fusca} (L.) Aiton fil. in Aiton,{\i  Hort. Kew.} ed. 2,{\b  1}: 127 (1810). Rhizome far-creeping; stems 15-35 cm, scarcely caespitose. Leaves up to 15 cm × 1 mm; bulbils absent. Spikelets 6 mm, oblong-ovoid, reddish-brown, in a dense, terminal, ovoid cluster up to 12 × 10 mm, often with 1(-2) smaller axillary clusters below. Uppermost bract exceeding the terminal cluster by (10-)25-50 mm. Perianth-bristles 5-6, antrorsely barbed. Nut smooth. 2n = 32.{\i  Bog-pools. N., W. & C. Europe, extending southwards to N. Italy.} Au Be Br Cz Da Fe Ga Ge Hb He Ho It Ju No Po Rs (N, B, C) Su.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 3. R. rugosa} (Vahl) S. Gale,{\i  Rhodora}{\b  46}: 93 (1944). Rhizome short; stems 40-65 cm, caespitose. Leaves 20-35 cm × 1·5-3 mm, somewhat glaucous. Spikelets c. 4 mm, ovoid, dark brown, in an irregular, diffuse panicle. Uppermost bract shorter or longer than inflorescence. Perianth-bristles 6, antrorsely barbed. Nut transversely rugulose.{\i  Wet places. S.W. Spain, W. Portugal.} Hs Lu. ({\i Tropics and subtropics}.)
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28   The records of this species from the Iberian peninsula and N.W. Africa are very few, and are very remote from the rest of its distribution-range, but there is no evidence to suggest that the plant has been introduced by man.
